'''Nehebkau Festival''' is an ancient Egyptian festival
==Overview==
{{Infobox hieroglyphs
|NAME = <hiero>W3-G21-V28-D58-Z9-D28:Z2-D30</hiero>
|NAME-TRANSCRIPTION = Heb-Neheb-kau<br/> ''ḥb-Nḥb-k3w''
|NAME-EXPLANATION = ''Festival of Neheb-kau''
}}

The {{ill|Ancient Egypt|de|Altägypten|ja|古代エジプト|zh|古埃及|lt=altägyptische|12=draft}} '''{{ill|Nehebkau|de|Nehebkau|ja|ネヘブカウ|zh|内赫布考|12=draft}}-Festival''' (also known as '''{{ill|Horus Festival|de|Horus-Fest|ja|ホルス祭|zh|荷鲁斯节|lt=Horus-Fest|12=draft}}''') has been attested since the {{ill|Old Kingdom (Egypt)|de|Altes Reich|ja|古王国|zh|古王国|lt=Old Kingdom|12=draft}} as a divine and royal "renewal festival" and lasted from the first to the second day of the first month of the season {{ill|Peret|de|Peret|ja|ペレト|zh|佩雷特|lt=Peret|12=draft}} ({{ill|Tybi|de|Tybi|ja|ティビ|zh|提比|12=draft}}); at the same time, it functioned as the "New Year Festival of {{ill|Horus|de|Horus|ja|ホルス|zh|荷鲁斯|12=draft}}".

== Background ==
=== Festival Course ===
The {{ill|God of the Dead|de|Totengott|ja|死者の神|zh|死神|12=draft}} {{ill|Nehebkau|de|Nehebkau|ja|ネヘブカウ|zh|内赫布考|12=draft}} acted in the {{ill|Duat|de|Duat|ja|ドゥアト|zh|Duat|12=draft}} as one of the judges in the {{ill|Judgment of the Dead|de|Totengericht|ja|死者の裁き|zh|死者审判|12=draft}} and evaluated the character traits of {{ill|Selfishness|de|Egoismus|ja|エゴイズム|zh|利己主义|lt=Selbstsucht|12=draft}} and {{ill|Arrogance|de|Hochmut|ja|高慢|zh|傲慢|12=draft}}. During the {{ill|Ceremony|de|Zeremonie|ja|儀式|zh|仪式|12=draft}}, Nehebkau assumed the role of the assistant and, in recognition of the achievements, once again bestowed the divine crown of the ruler after the completion of a year.

The first day was dedicated to the deity {{ill|Amun-Ra|de|Amun-Re|ja|アモン・ラー|zh|阿蒙-拉|12=draft}}, in {{ill|Edfu|de|Edfu|ja|エドフ|zh|埃德富|12=draft}} to Horus as the son of {{ill|Ra|de|Re|ja|ラー|zh|拉|lt=Re|12=draft}}. During the voyage of Amun-Ra in his {{ill|Solar Bark|de|Barke|ja|太陽の舟|zh|太阳之舟|lt=Sonnenbarke|12=draft}}, Nehebkau renewed the divine rulership. On the morning of the second day, the populace participated in the {{ill|Procession|de|Prozession|ja|行列|zh|游行|12=draft}} of the king, who was now ritually confirmed by Nehebkau himself {{ill|ritual|de|Ritual|ja|儀式|zh|仪式|lt=rituell|12=draft}}. A festival record from {{ill|Ramses III|de|Ramses III.|ja|ラムセス3世|zh|拉美西斯三世|12=draft}} has been preserved:

{{Zitat|1.&nbsp;Peret&nbsp;I, New Year’s Day of Horus: The day of the appearance of King Horus of Edfu, the son of Ra, beloved by the people. Every ceremony should be performed as on {{ill|1. Achet I|de|Achet|ja|アシェト I|zh|阿切特 I|lt=1. Achet I|12=draft}}.|Edfou V, 351, 3–4}}

=== Proclamation Festival under Ramses II ===
The Nehebkau Festival under {{ill|Ramses II|de|Ramses II.|ja|ラムセス2世|zh|拉美西斯二世|12=draft}} also had the character of a proclamation festival, as the reigning king ({{ill|Pharaoh|de|Pharao|ja|ファラオ|zh|法老|12=draft}}) proclaimed special {{ill|jubilees|de|Jubiläum|ja|記念祭|zh|庆典|lt=Jubiläen|12=draft}} of the king during the celebrations.

Well-documented are the proclamations of Ramses II from the regnal years 42, 45, 51, 54, 63, and 66 for the {{ill|Sed Festival|de|Sedfest|ja|セド祭|zh|塞德节|12=draft}} numbers 5, 6, 8, 9, 12, and 13. Deviating from this, in the 57th and 60th regnal years, the proclamation for {{ill|Sed Festival|de|Sedfest|ja|セド祭|zh|塞德节|12=draft}} numbers 10 and 11 was made on 17 Peret II with a fifteen‐day delay.

== Literature ==
* {{ill|Siegfried Schott|de|Siegfried Schott|ja|ジークフリート・ショット|zh|西格弗里德·肖特|12=draft}}: ''Ancient Egyptian Festival Dates'' (= ''Academy of Sciences and Literature. Proceedings of the Humanities and Social Sciences Class'' 1950, Volume 10, {{ISSN|0002-2977}}). Publisher of the Academy of Sciences and Literature, among others, Mainz, 1950.

